**SLIDE 10 — Dashboard — Scans in Seconds**

*"This is what the dashboard looks like. Every scan, every finding, every repository — in one place, in real time. What you're seeing here is a scan completing in seconds. Not hours, not a weekly report — seconds, on every code change. For leadership, this means for the first time there is actual visibility into the security posture of our codebase. No more guessing. No more finding out after the fact. This is what proactive security looks like."*

---

**SLIDE 11 — Use Case: Command Injection**

*"Let me show you one specific example so this isn't abstract. Command injection is a type of vulnerability where an attacker can send input to an application that gets executed as a system command. In simple terms — if a piece of code takes something a user types and passes it directly to the operating system without checking it first, an attacker can type in a command instead of normal input. They can read files, delete data, or take full control of the system. It's one of the most common and most dangerous vulnerability types. Semgrep detects this automatically — it identifies exactly where the unsafe input is, flags it before the code ships, and tells the developer what to change."*

---

**SLIDE 12 — Source, Sink & Fix Guidance**

*"Here's what makes Semgrep particularly valuable for developers. When it finds an issue, it doesn't just say 'there's a problem.' It shows the source — where the untrusted input enters the code. It shows the sink — where that input ends up being used dangerously. And it provides fix guidance — exactly what to change and why. This means a developer with no security background can understand and resolve the issue themselves, immediately. It removes the dependency on a dedicated security team to review every finding. Security knowledge is built into the workflow."*

